NAME
    termcap(4) 		- terminal capabilities

SYNOPSIS
    /etc/termcap

DESCRIPTION
    The "termcap" file contains definitions which yield the
    properties of different types of terminals. Each definition
    has many optional entries, for example, the number of lines
    on the device and the string to clear the screen.

    Each program which wishes to treat the output device as
    something more powerful than a stream of bytes, should use
    the termcap(3) routines. These routines look in the "termcap"
    capability file and retrieve the properties of the current
    terminal.

    The user should make sure that a definition exists in the
    "termcap" file, and then set the environment variable $TERM
    to the name of the current terminal.


    BUILDING YOUR OWN TERMCAP ENTRY

    Each "termcap" entry consists of a list of alternate names for 
    the terminal, followed by codes describing its properties. The
    names are separated by '|' characters, and the definitions by
    ':'s. If a line ends with a '\' then the entry continues on the
    following line.

    For historical reasons, the first name is two characters long.
    The last name is simply a comment. Only the second name is 
    currently checked by the Minix termcap(3). An example is,

	mx|minix|console:\
	    :bs:co#80:li#24:\
	    :cd=\E[0J:cl=\E[H\E[0J:\
	    :so=\E[7m:se=\E[0m:\
	    :sr=\EM:\
	    :cm=\E[%i%d;%dH:\
	    :ho=\E[H:


    The first two codes do not take any arguments, include
    them if your terminal has the corresponding function.

	am		Right off end of line wraps to next line
	bs		Ctrl/H performs a backspace


    Define the size of the display.

	co#		Number of columns
	li#		Number of lines


    All of the following codes take a string argument. Within
    strings certain escape codes are allowed:

		^x	Ctrl/x
		\xxx	Octal code
		\200	Null 	  (^@)
		\b	Backspace (^H)
		\t	Tab	  (^I)
		\n	Newline   (^J)
		\f	Formfeed  (^L)
		\r	Return	  (^M)
		\E	Escape 	  (^[)
		\072	:
		\\	\
		\^	^


    There are three codes for different clearing functions.

	ce		Clear to end of line
	cd		Clear to end of screen
	cl		Clear the whole screen


    If the terminal can change the mode of the display for
    subsequently output characters, then set the relevant
    entries described below. The "mx" entries are for
    ANSI compatible terminals.

	so		Start "stand out" mode (usually reverse)
	se		End "stand out" mode
	us		Start underscore mode (sometimes bold)
	ue		End underscore mode
	mb		Start blinking mode
	md		Start bold mode
	mr		Start reverse mode (same as "so")
	me		Return to normal mode


    The following is only available on a few terminals.

	sr		Scroll backwards


    There is a definition for cursor motion.

	cm		Cursor motion

    The string for "cm" acts like a printf() command, with the
    destination line and column as arguments. There are some '%'
    format commands which control the printing of the output
    string when tgoto(3) is used:

		%d	Print as a number (%2d)
		%+c	Print as a character (after adding 'c')
		%i	Increment before output
		%%	Print a '%'


    The following are simpler cursor movements, try to
    define these if "cm" is not appropriate for your terminal.

	up		Up one line
	do		Down one line
	le		Left one space
	nd		Right one space
	ho		Move to top left corner


    Each of the following are set to the string generated by 
    certain special function keys on the keyboard. If the key
    does not exist, then no definition need be supplied.

	ku		String generated by "UP"
	kd		String generated by "DOWN"
	kl		String generated by "LEFT"
	kr		String generated by "RIGHT"
	kh		String generated by "HOME"
	k0		String generated by "END"
	k1		String generated by "PGUP"
	k2		String generated by "PGDN"
	k3		String generated by numeric "+"
	k4		String generated by numeric "-"
	k5		String generated by numeric "5"


    NOTES

    Try to at least define "co#", "li#", "cl", "so", "se"
    and "ho". Programs should be able to always find these
    entries.

    The following commands also require additional termcap 
    entries:

	blank		"cm"
	elle		"cm"
	ic		"cm"
	mined		"cm", "sr"


FILES
    /etc/termcap	The termcap entries

SEE ALSO
    termcap(1), termcap(3)

BUGS
    Some termcaps allow delay parameters. The Minix termcap(3)
    does not handle them.

    There are some useful "%" format commands that are not described
    here because tgoto(3) does not support them.

    Mined does not call termcap(3), but has the strings built-in.

    Not all entries are checked by users of termcap(3).
    Especially the "kx" entries.

    If a terminal does not support "cm", then it is the application's
    responsibility to use "ho", "do" and "nd".

    The entries described in termcap(4) are only a subset of the
    ones available under Unix.
